Barack Obama wins Nobel Peace Prize as fourth US president
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth US president in history.
He will receive a diploma, medal and check for $1.4 million, among other things, for his exceptional efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and will be busy.
First, he will visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of the committee that selected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple are then scheduled to meet with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will win it as the fourth US president, but only the third to receive the award in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The president does not want to avoid this topic, because he realizes that he is accepting the award as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, something none of his critics will fail to point out.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for ten million Swedish kroner (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate them to charity, but has not yet decided on a specific charity.
The busy schedule will then take the president and his wife to a banquet where, in addition to the Norwegian king and queen, the prime minister and 250 other invited guests will be present.
From the beginning, Obama was rather reticent about the price.
He said, for example, that he felt he did not fully deserve it.
He also reiterated several times that it is not just a prize for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was a "call to action" for him.
