"Paroubek's" budget took money for pensions and sick leave
After the left has added farmers or officials, contrary to the government's opinion, there may not be money in the budget for pensions, sickness or building savings.
But also on interest on the national debt or on international litigation.
It will cause problems for those who will govern in the second half of next year, says Finance Minister Eduard Janota.
When the Social Democrats and Communists pushed for increases for some groups, they relied on the government to borrow additional money for sensitive expenses, pensions, or sick pay. "It's just postponing problems to the future, laying mines," Janota says.
The borrowed money is paid more and more interest and must sometimes be returned.
The state does not have much choice where to take it.
If they do not reduce social benefits or the cost of running the state, they must raise taxes.
To all those now added by the left: firefighters, teachers, farmers.
And later to their children.
People do not have to worry about pensions or sick leave, from whose account 1.8 billion disappeared, they will get them.
However, at the cost of the state becoming more indebted – next year, not only 163 billion will be missing in the coffers, but more.
Despite Minister Janota's efforts, the debt will grow faster and faster, and with it the cost of interest.
The state will need money to pay for it, and it will no longer be enough to slightly increase VAT or reduce maternity leave, as the government did in its anti-deficit package.
Due to shifts of money to several groups of voters, there will also be a shortfall of five billion next year for the completion of highways and railways.
These are mostly already tendered and unfinished sections that cannot be redesigned and possibly cheapened.
At most, to mothball, which is also not free.
This means delaying or stopping thirty large constructions, and drawing European money is also at risk, warns Karel Hanzelka, spokesman for the Ministry of Transport.
The ČSSD proposed that it would solve the loss of money in a Solomonic way – it would reach into ČEZ's dividends, which the state mostly owns, and from them it would pour in the transport fund.
The problem is that the amount of the dividend is never certain, and it is certainly not a bottomless resource.
Last year, CZK 18 billion came from ČEZ to the budget.
