USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is almost comical with what schoolboy diligence Barack Obama, a president with a reputation for being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he considered the most stupid, on the Afghan issue.
When he finally sweated out his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it from Bush's Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward."
Three years ago, he criticized Bush's idea of sending fresh troop reinforcements to civil war Iraq as an "irresponsible and disastrous decision."
But the months that followed showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field commanders, was the only possible and highly successful strategy to the point that Iraq is now not mentioned in news reports.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively he left his successor with a much more grateful starting point than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
He was again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, notably the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the reluctant gunmen in the White House, despite subordination customs.
He asked for 40,000 men to turn the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he cheated the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to squeeze another 5,000 out of Europe, even though he had originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic part of Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in as little as 18 months and complete the process within three years. The entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than it answers.
Many doubt that a half-scale increase will bear the same fruit as the Iraq move.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well ordered, with its leaders honoring agreements.
The Afghan situation is characterised by the opposite symptom - no one can be relied upon and no agreements are being honoured.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing masters every day as they see fit, are poorly prepared.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain a Potemkin village beyond which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily difficult, given the lack of clarity that makes Pakistani and Iranian influences even more difficult.
Even the construction of an "operational state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, does not seem very realistic.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is striking in its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of exploding.
To believe that soldiers sent into the turmoil of war for the purpose of "returning home soon" will cause the miracle done here can only be truly romantic, untouched by reality.
Politically, setting a date for troop withdrawal is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will see it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans' willingness to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is approaching the negative.
European politicians do not know how and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically intervening in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the United States will face the difficult question of whether to try to solve the problem by military force.
An answer will be needed just as Obama believes America is moving toward a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any such solution will also mark a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only band-aid for Barack Obama is that with three years to go before the presidential election, there is still plenty of time left for him to come up with another strategy if it proves to be a total failure.
Goldman Sachs executives no longer receive cash bonuses
Senior executives at the US bank Goldman Sachs will not receive cash bonuses this year.
The announcement was made by the company, which is responding to sharp criticism of its wage practices.
Instead of money, a group of 30 top executives will receive shares that can be sold in five years at the earliest.
