Britain announced on Wednesday that it intends to impose a one-off tax on bankers' bonuses in excess of £25,000 (roughly CZK 712,000).
France is preparing similar steps.
This year, women won Nobel Prizes in all disciplines except physics
A record five women received this year's Nobel Prize in the professional categories and literature from King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden in Stockholm today.
In addition to the four female scientists, the German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller, was among them.
The Nobel Prize in Medicine was awarded to two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, along with their compatriot Jack Szostak for their research on chromosomes.
The Chemistry Prize went to Israeli Ada Jonath along with Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishnan and Thomas Steitz for elucidating the structure and function of ribosomes.
The last laureate was the Nobel Prize in Economics, which went to the American Elinor Ostrom and her compatriot Oliver Williamson for their analyses of economic governance.
The only professional category that went without a holder this year was physics.
The prize went to Charles Kao for his research in the field of optical fibers and George Smith and Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which is the basis of all digital cameras, fax machines or astronomical telescopes.
Each winner received a diploma, a Nobel medal and a certificate of financial reward.
For each category, it amounts to ten million Swedish kronor (approximately CZK 25 million).
If there are more winners in each of them, they share the reward among themselves.
