Mandela is played by Morgan Freeman in Clint Eastwood's novelty
South Africans say the new Hollywood film Invictus: Undefeated will tell the world a lot about the country, its struggle and victories, despite some criticism that American actors play the lead roles.
The story is about sports, race and Nelson Mandela.
The tireless fighter against the racist apartheid regime in South Africa and its first black president, Nelson Mandela, is portrayed in his life story by Oscar-winning American actor Morgan Freeman.
Freeman said ninety-one-year-old Mandela asked him if he could play him in Eastwood's film.
Another notable role in it is played by Matt Damon.
I told him, 'If I'm going to play you, I'm going to have to have access to you.
The seventy-two-year-old actor, who won an award for his role in Eastwood's boxing drama A Million Dollar Baby, has played the leader of the slave-turned-slave movement, the fictional president of the United States, and even the god in Divine Evan, but rarely someone who is still alive and as important to many people as Mandela.
The former South African statesman was sentenced to 27 years in prison for his active work to end apartheid in South Africa.
He was released in 1990 and became president of the country for four years.
In 1993 he was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
Invictus is the Latin word for undefeated and is the title of a poem by English author William Ernest Henley published in 1875.
The challenge was to talk like him
The film is the true story of how Nelson Mandela joined forces with South African rugby team captain Francois Pienaar to help unite the country. President-elect Mandela knows that his nation remains racially and economically divided after apartheid.
He believes that he can unite his people through sport, so he decides to unite rugby players, who are among the underdogs worldwide.
The South African team eventually qualified for the 1995 World Cup.
Freeman worked for several years to bring Mandela's story to the screen.
"I had no other goal than to play this role in a way that brought it as close to reality as possible," Freeman said.
The biggest challenge, of course, was to speak like him.
The actor said that if he and the world politician were from the same area, he would try to meet Mandela, dine with him, be backstage before his speech.
Most importantly, he wanted to shake Mandela's hand.
"I found that when I squeezed your hand, I took your energy, it was transmitted, and I felt like I knew how you felt," he said.
It's important for me to try to become a different person.
Matt Damon plays François Pienaar, the captain of the white national rugby team.
The actor said he had six months to prepare for a role in the tough world of rugby.
The big surprise for him was when he first met Pienaar in his house.
I remember ringing the doorbell, he opened it for me and the first thing I said to François Pienaar in my life was, 'I look much bigger in a movie'.
Despite the distinct differences in the characters' characters compared to their real-life counterparts under Eastwood's direction, Invictus: Undefeated received positive reviews and Oscar ambitions.
Daily Variety film critic Todd McCarthy summed up his assessment in the words: "It was a very good story, a very well made film."
In movie reviews on rottentomatoes.com websites, Invictus received 76 percent positive ratings.
The secret of the glow over Norway solved: The Russians tested a missile
A strange light effect of unknown origin could be observed over Norway.
The Russian Defense Ministry only admitted yesterday that it had tested an intercontinental ballistic missile near the Norwegian border.
The launch was again unsuccessful and the missile referred to as the "Bulava" type, which was originally supposed to be the pride of the Russian army, is slowly becoming a nightmare for Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Even his repeated presence in the tests of the rocket did not have a proper effect on the success of test flights.
Bulava usually did not take off at all or was damaged in the air.
Russian newspapers already refer to "Bulava" as "a rocket that does not fly".
A rocket that does not fly but shines
This 13th attempt was initially normal.
Only at the end of the flight was the technical damage of the apparatus again.
Apparently, the engine in the third stage of the rocket exploded.
This time, "Bulava" took off from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donsky, which sailed under the surface of the White Sea.
This type of missile allows you to shoot from a vessel that is both in motion and submerged.
Therefore, it is likely that the mysterious light over Norway caused by an unspecified flying object was indeed a malfunctioning "Bulava".
After all, the Norwegians had no doubt from the first moment that it was a Russian missile.
This time, the generals defend themselves, arguing that it is impossible to speak unequivocally of failure.
The first two stages of the rocket lasted and the accident affected only the third.
In previous cases, the engines failed in the first stage.
Although not a single test launch took place flawlessly, only six out of thirteen are considered unsuccessful by the leadership of the Ministry of Defence.
Almost fifty percent success rate therefore fills the generals with optimism and so they still claim that the "Bulava" will one day fly without problems and that it can even carry up to ten hypersonic nuclear units with a maximum total weight of 1.15 tons.
