Czech discovery: a substance that works even on 'hardy' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow down the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it works even on viruses that have already acquired immunity against drugs.
In some cases, this outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on the common variant of the virus as some already available drugs.
AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, patients can significantly prolong the life of a mixture of drugs that prevent the reproduction of HIV in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, the incomplete suppression of the reproduction of the virus results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the Institute of Chemical Technology Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of the HIV virus.
Metallocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all drugs used today and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new 'improved' compounds prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to a viral protein.
Metallocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Treacherous and resilient virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV-protease-induced splitting of the HIV virus, mature infectious viral particles would not have formed.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically altered.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of agents against HIV protease was tested in a test tube and also against its resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallocarboranes on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as with clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants, against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications make metallocarboranes interesting compounds for further research leading to the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
