Vaccination against pneumococci will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococci from January will break the established habits.
It is to be the first to be free for families and at the same time optional.
But there are already voices that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The Institute of Medicine is already setting maximum prices for vaccines to be paid for by health insurance companies.
Experts are also already clear about the vaccination procedure.
New vaccination
Free vaccines for August children
Since January, children born on or after August 2 last year can be vaccinated against pneumococci free of charge.
The condition is that they have not yet received a single dose of vaccination.
Those who started vaccinating last year or earlier must also pay for another booster vaccination.
The first dose of vaccination must be given between 3 and 5 months of age.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococci.
Parents paid 1600 crowns for one dose or more.
When vaccinating the youngest children, four doses are needed.
Overall, experts estimate that health insurance companies will spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns a year on vaccination doses.
But it will save on treatment that children without vaccination would need.
Until now, the state has given about 500,000 a year for all blanket vaccinations of children.
Reimbursed vaccination was introduced by the so-called Janot package.
Pneumococcus causes otitis media, but also serious infections including meningitis and blood poisoning.
According to investigations in hospitals, up to 28 children under 10 years of age die of pneumococcal infection in our country every year.
In addition to the Czech Republic, they have introduced reimbursed blanket vaccination of children against pneumococci in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, however, there are opinions that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
From January, it is to be covered by insurance companies and optional.
Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the Nahlas civic association, suggested that mandatory vaccination would be better.
His association has long promoted pneumococcal vaccines.
Experts at the international conference in which our association participated were not completely satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that at least this has been achieved.
"I think that's the path we have to take now," Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the procedure of vaccination against pneumococci.
At the moment, we are not considering it at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say
Hana Cabrnochová, chairwoman of the Professional Society of Paediatric Practitioners, acknowledges that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children were vaccinated, a reduction in booster shots could be considered: "With this vaccine costing such a high amount, we quite understand the political decision that the vaccination was started as voluntary," Cabrnoch said.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of new parents to vaccinate their infants against pneumococci by next year.
Vaccination against pneumococci is also a breakthrough in that it is the first blanket vaccination of children covered by health insurance companies, not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend money on prevention, saving on further treatment, Cabrnoch explains.
Doctors will have to buy the substances themselves
But this is related to the concerns of general paediatricians about buying vaccines.
According to the original plan, the vaccines would be purchased by insurance companies, and doctors would receive them in a similar way that the state supplies them with substances for other vaccinations.
