Can a Muslim be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters were calling for a ban on minarets and alarmist reports about the alleged Islamization of Europe are generally spreading, John Bowen, an American academic, has written and reported, wondering whether Muslims can integrate — and will — into one of the continent's most open secular societies.
After reading this book, some of the readers became admirers of the author's latest work, "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves" (2006), this elegant and debated study of the contentious issues that have divided and occupied the country for 15 years, and whose effects are still felt today.
Mr. Bowen's latest book has a broader and much more ambitious scope.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media have said about Islam in France, but what really happened.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now house 5 ÷ 6 million French Muslims, what Mr. Bowen calls "Islamic spaces."
He is a good listener, reproducing debates between teachers and students on the issues that concern them most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should a young Muslim be taught about gay development and rights?
Can a Muslim woman marry a man who is not a Muslim?
Does a Muslim have the right to use an interest-based banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane contentious issues that are discussed, and that are part of everyday life rather than the political dramas that occupy the media.
The author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, including well-known figures, including Tariq Ramadan, an Arab, Swiss-born Muslim scholar and academic.
This new generation is trying to open up a debate about how to be a good Muslim and a good citizen at the same time in a modern secular society.
They have no arguments for all their customs.
Conservatives are suspicious of the real idea of French or European Islam.
The philosophers and activists interviewed by Mr. Bowen are inclined to believe that it is the antithesis of Selafi—the supporters of the purist Sunni Islam associated in Saudi Arabia—a group small but influential in European Muslims.
Mr Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism are compatible.
But adaptation requires compromises on both sides.
It asks how far French politicians (and the intellectual elite that so doggedly defend the lay public) are really committed to the idea of pluralism.
He believes that Muslims probably have less experience in matters of faith than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who have also had to make historic compromises with secular republicanism.
Rather than developing pragmatism, he found a "tightening of the screws of values."
Can a Muslim be French? After reading this book, someone may be inclined to say, "Yes, but not now."
