In aging China, changing course
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters reading that "Mother Earth is too exhausted to support more children" and "One more child means one more grave."
Then they learned the lesson that when official government bodies in Shanghai, alarmed by the low birth rate and aging population in their city, suddenly changed course this summer and began encouraging young couples, their response was immediate and determined: Never.
We have always devoted all our time and energy to just one child.
"We didn't save anything for others," says Wang, 31, a human resources administrator who has an 8-month-old son.
China's more than 30-year-long policy of having only one child has been established, creating two generations of notoriously chubby and pampered children, affectionately dubbed "little emperors," and a population crisis threatens the country.
The average birth rate fell to 1.8 children per couple, compared to six before the policy came into force, according to UN data.
A population breakdown where the population aged 60 and over is predicted to grow from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. That's far above the overall average of around 20 percent.
The imbalance is greater in wealthy coastal cities with populations with higher education, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over made up nearly 22 percent of Shanghai's registered residents, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai City Commission on Population and Family Planning, said many couples must have children to "help reduce the proportion of an aging population and a shrinking workforce in the future."
He says it's about "being old doesn't mean being rich -- like in developed countries like Japan or Sweden."
Gradual calming
As inserted into the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is probably the most controversial mandate established under the Communist Party to this day.
Couples who violated the policy faced enormous fines – up to three times their annual salary in some areas – and discrimination at work.
Chinese officials have championed policies that have helped the country prevent critical exploitation of natural resources, while human rights defenders have been slammed for pursuing the policy.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women to undergo abortions with their second child.
In addition, many couples have had to undergo sexist selective abortions, leading to an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, population officials have been gradually more lenient in their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they typically allowed a number of exceptions - including city dwellers, members of national minorities, and cases where a man and a woman were only children - and in 2007 they softened the wording of their hard-line slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Peking University's Institute of Population Research, said central government officials had previously discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners was an only child.
In June, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost overnight, posters urging parents to have only one child were replaced by copies of the ordinance, detailing how legitimate it would be to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration sent family planning officers and volunteers to meet couples in their homes and slip leaflets under the door.
They also promised to provide emotional and financial counseling for those who decided to have more than one child.
The response was cold, family planning officials said.
Grieving response
Although officials in one rural city around Shanghai have seen an increase in interest from couples who would like to have a second child after the campaign began, most city precincts did not report changes.
Huinan County, with a population of 115,000, for example, still registered four to five cases per month.
