The UN group outlined a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by largely unruly attitudes and mutual recrimination -- refocused Friday on releasing a document that proposes ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden at the earliest date.
The text, which can provide the basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as illuminates the way forward.
But there was important progress in the negotiations, which took place at the wrong time with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Produced by the UN ad hoc working group, this text discreetly states how much money rich countries should give to poor countries to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a variety of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies so that they can limit their carbon output, and what should be the upper limit to the global temperature rise that policymakers will still be able to tolerate.
That will give the process a great deal of flexibility, said John Coequyt, a senior executive at the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, is an abridged from 180 pages of text from the meeting to focus on what the top climate official at the UN, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture".
It outlines the outlines of a possible agreement in which industrialized nations could collectively limit their emissions to 25 to 45 percent by a year compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent over that period.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union rushed through a pledge on Friday to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries embrace adaptation to climate change — from managing floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Still, Friday featured the same kind of verbal fireworks that prevalent in last week's interviews.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Action Todd Stern dismissed a speech calling for binding cuts in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries compared to voluntary for major emerging economies if they were not funded by the developed world.
The shift signaled that the Obama administration had taken a harder line on China than Bush administration officials had done just two years ago.
The United States will not accede to the treaty without transferring major developing countries and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text was not sufficient to secure the restrictions and should be vetted by outside observers.
Stern made the comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei told the U.S. chief climate negotiator that either a lack of "common sense" or "extreme irresponsibility" led to a message earlier in the week that the United States would not help China financially to deal with global warming.
With the future of the world's major powers economic careers at stake, a tug-of-war has erupted both within the developing world and between the industrialized world and emerging economies.
The current struggle is mostly over the preservation of individual economies rather than the preservation of the planet, between China and the United States over the fulfillment of their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that two dozen of the world's most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take stronger action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate to Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers were fighting over who should bear the costs of limiting greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries had become much more aggressive in finding a way to prevent large emitters responsibly from taking action.
It's clearly a game of new economic hegemony unfolding, said Ulate, who also serves as a regional advisor on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for international conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the effects of climate change indicated that they would like to continue pushing for a legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most of the main participants said that the best outcome of the talks would be a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push by small island nations "has triggered a political crackdown on the entire political process" in part because they are now united and demanding action from growing economies such as China and India.
The meeting created new urgency once delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the remaining issues before heads of government could compete for an agreement.
High-ranking officials, such as India's Environmental Protection Minister Yairam Ramesh and China's deputy minister, stepped off planes and ran through the halls of the Bella Center to closed doors for meetings and new conferences to lay out claims that will be considered next week.
The sheer sheer size of the rally - with 13,000 people moving to and from the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists staging ironic spectacles at night about the countries they thought had sent them, and hand-to-hand proposals passed on paper rather than e-mail -- dominated by the challenge.
The intensity is only a superstructure: almost all the key ministers were present in Copenhagen, and earlier on Wednesday 60 heads of state.
"We have fallen into high categories," said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, deputy minister for global policy at international nature conservation.
Heavyweights are coming.
Britain's first 140-mph-hour train redefined feelings this Monday
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle cut through the darkness to signal the departure of the train that revolutionized transport in Britain.
The country's first high-speed passenger train reaches 140 miles per hour and flies from Ashford, Kent, to London's St Pancras, covering a distance of 58 miles in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, Secretary of State for Transport, then joined Mrs. Kelly Holmes in boarding the first high-speed passenger train outside Lndyn.
He hopes the new service will eventually connect Britain to an international network of fast, reliable trains and connect the major conurbations of Midland, North and Scotland to London.
Neglected stagnant waters should reduce passenger and business travel times, and switching from planes and cars to rail could reduce carbon emissions and eliminate congestion on the roads.
Theoretically, the three major political parties have allowed themselves to be won over to this vision.
But the tens of trillions of pounds required to build a new national rail network, the inevitable battle for projects and environmental concerns have now put the brakes on the construction of Britain's high-speed lines.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company formed in January to provide the government with a workable study, handed over its report to Lord Adonis on December 30, the Times reported.
It provided him with a detailed route map of the next planned stage of the high-speed network.
The new routing of London's connection to West Midland has been proposed to within five metres in urban areas and neighbourhoods where environmental degradation could be problematic.
In the open countryside, up to 25 m of the final route was planned.
HS2 also envisages identifying three options for a large-scale high-speed network running north.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred option is the Y-shaped conscription, with one high-speed line running to West Midland.
The line would split near Birmingham with one branch running from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another running northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle am Tyne.
One line should lead to Scotland.
"It looks like the most powerful choice has been made," said a railroad expert.
Once this is done, travel times between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to two hours and 40 minutes.
The first stage, which will not open before 2025, could allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to more than one hour in the present.
The proposals would allow trains to travel at 2250 miles per hour, making the British network the fastest in Europe.
The initial line is already being designed to carry 400 m long trains capable of carrying 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains could operate every hour on the London-Birmingham line.
This means that the London terminal would be able to serve up to 20,000 passengers per hour if needed.
Due to capital constraints, it is envisaged that the existing station would be expanded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Experts from the railway industry say that only San Pancras International or Euston offer such potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he intends to implement the scheme, but extensive public consultation and planning processes mean that a final decision will not be made before the general election.
Even if it sets the wheels in motion, the network should be built piecemeal.
Trains should first be put into service not on high-speed lines but on existing lines north of Birmingham, keeping travel times between London and Scotland above three hours.
This is seen as a crucial point of contact for ensuring the transition from aircraft to trains, a landmark for the railway revolution.
