Separatist Abkhazia elects president, Georgia denounces it as a "farce"
Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, about a year after Moscow recognized the pro-Russian separatist territory as independent from Georgia, while Tbilisi called the move a "farce."
Some 131,000 people were invited to participate in these first elections after the August 2008 Russo-Georgian war for control of South Ossetia, another former Georgian territory recognized by Russia.
Polling stations closed at 17:00 GMT.
According to officials of the Abkhaz Election Commission, turnout was 58% a few hours before polling stations closed.
The first preliminary results should be announced overnight from Saturday to Sunday.
All five candidates, including incumbent President Sergei Bagapsha, categorically reject the idea of reunification with Georgia, which condemned the election.
This election is a farce.
On the other hand, Georgian President Mikheil Saakashvili "regrets that Abkhazia has completely fallen into Russian rule," said his spokeswoman, Manana Manjgaladze.
Apart from Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this territory of 216,000 people, while the rest of the world considers it part of Georgia, which was illegally occupied by Russian troops.
After separation from Georgia, after the conflict of 1992-1993, in which several thousand people died, Abkhazia is trying to show through the elections that it is ready to return to international politics.
This process is one stage of our new life, a new era of our independent state, Kvarchiya Svetlana, a 54-year-old historian who also admitted that she had voted for President Bagapsh, told AFP.
She was one of those who came to vote at a polling station at a school in the capital, Sukhumi, in a beautiful white building with several palm trees at the entrance.
The issue of Russian dominance is the main issue of the presidential elections in this region on the shores of the Black Sea, which boasts beautiful nature.
Across the small country of 216,000 people, huge billboards with Bagapsh are placed next to Russian President Dmitry Medvedev and Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
