"We Abkhazians are grateful," he said in a small ceremony, referring to Moscow's support and, in particular, its decision to recognize Abkhazia's independence.
I hope that your country will soon be recognized by the United Nations, said Alexei Ostrovsky, a member of the Russian parliament, drinking a glass of vodka.
The opposition, which was represented in the election by former Vice President Raul Khadzhimba and two businessmen, Zaus Ardzinba and Beslan Boutba, criticized the treaties struck with Moscow last year, such as the one that allows Russia to control Abkhazia's rail network for 10 years.
The fifth candidate, Vitali Bganba, says he supports neither the current government nor the opposition.
An absolute majority of 50% plus one vote is required to win an election.
If none of the candidates achieves this result, the runoff must take place within two weeks.
