The UDF raises the tone and calls on the Nouveau Centre party to no longer use their acronym.
The UDF, controlled by François Bayrou's MoDem party, on Friday responded to an attempt by Nouveau Centre party president, Hervé Morin, to appropriate the acronym of Giscard's former party, saying it could not be used in any media outlet under threat of prosecution.
Hervé Morin has publicly announced his intention to appropriate the acronym UDF, saying that François Bayrou does not deserve to bear its legacy after shaking hands with the left.
The defence minister, whose party is a partner of the UMP, planned to confirm the strategy on Saturday before the National Council of the Nouveau Centre (NC).
This move gained the support of MP Hervé de Charetto (former UMP, now for NC), who claims ownership of the UDF brand because he first registered it with the National Industrial Property Institute (l'Institut national de la propriété industrielle) in 2004.
But on Friday evening, a committee of the UDF Association, run by friends of François Bayrou who have no intention of being expropriated, came out of its silence and made a formal request to both the minister and the MP to stop using the acronym and hand back ownership of the trademark, under threat of criminal prosecution.
In recent days, you have raised alarming statements that you will propose to your political movement +retake+ the abbreviation UDF, the Association writes in its letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the committee, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez of the MoDem party and Senator Jean Arthuis of the Alliance centriste.
At the same time, you have considered it appropriate to place the name +Nouveau centre+, with the slogan +UDF of today+, on your promotional materials and on the welcome website of your movement, the signatories of the letter also state.
As you know, you have no right to use this abbreviation, explains the UDF Committee, which asks the NC movement to "immediately remove all references to the UDF name from all promotional materials, including (its) website".
At the same time, he asks Hervé de Charette "to hand over ownership of the trademark to the legitimate owners".
If you fail to do so, we will turn to the courts to ensure that the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members are respected, the signatories warn.
In their letter, they state that the UDF "has been a full-fledged political movement since 1978" and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends "chose" to leave in 2007 "to form a rival movement, as others did in 2002, to establish the UMP.
The Nouveau Centre movement therefore has no right to use the abbreviation UDF (Union pour la démocratie française).
At the same time, they recall that the last UDF Congress voted in 2007 to join the MoDem for three years and to create a committee charged with defending the "moral and material interests" of the association founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
With regard to Hervé de Charette, the committee continues, "when he registered the trademark", he was "not a member of the UDF for three years" but of the UMP.
In a scandalous and fraudulent manner, he used the non-existent registration of the acronym to do so on his own account.
This tactlessness begins to turn into a crime, they declare, and then comment with irony on the NC strategy: "It seems to us that both in politics and in everyday life it is more valuable to make a name for oneself than to step out of anonymity by fraudulently adopting a name to which we have no right."
