Liliane Bettencourt, on the other hand, has always denied being manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a long-term friend.
While the court had to assess the merits of the lawsuit filed by Mrs. Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers' Friday court speech at times turned into a family hour of truth.
Liliana Bettencourt's lawyer produced three letters sent by his client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, expressing her distrust of Françoisa Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In a 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt, according to the lawyer, adds, "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once or twice a day for fifteen years.
Since she got married, I have never been able to talk to Françoise."
The Public Prosecutor's Office in Nanterre again found that the applicant's conduct was unjustified, all the more so because the guardianship judge had recently rejected her request to initiate proceedings for legal protection for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "is fully capable of participating in court, she is not protected or under guardianship.
No one else will act for her," confirmed the head of the prosecutor's office, Marie-Christine Daubigney.
The court eventually decided to comment on Ms Bettencourt-Meyers' legitimacy at the time the trial began.
Managerial Revolution or the End of Economic Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence has been in vain...
For more than a decade, the behavior of the management of large companies towards employees has resembled the attitude of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a matter of identifying with the "values" determined from above, as was the case before, when it was necessary to impose on the consumer products that arose from the ideas of the heads of factory technicians.
By making the customer the center of entrepreneurial companies, the marketing revolution has aligned market capture strategies in the right direction... Although authoritarian efforts to impose products different from customer preferences regularly return!
The passive attitude of employees can lead to fatal demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA and Renault are only the visible part of a much larger general phenomenon that affects mainly managerial cadres.
This demobilization adversely affects the development of all intellectual functions of society, including research and development, and more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires all stakeholders to (...) proactive attitude and anticipability" and requires commitments from employees that are completely contrary to the income of authoritarian management.
That is why we are calling for a managerial revolution that aims to put workers at the centre of the business as well as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls.
Internal opinion polls - such as the questionnaire presented to Orange employees - will contribute to a revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I am afraid not.
Mainly because I have already convinced myself that in the face of a new situation, the structure will return preferentially to it after various digressions... what she always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, as one of the pathologies of power, increases in proportion to the severity of its own failures.
Finally, because most executives have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Because they are college graduates for engineers, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
For the sake of intellectual convenience, they adopt the old behaviorist theory, currently revived by "neuroscience" from the USA and widely disseminated without much knowledge by scientific institutes and the media.
A recent Ipsos survey on the Figaro.fr website showed that it is possible to move the "levers" (sic) of managerial involvement, which only confirms executives in their position of mechanical control, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors.
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of a finite vision of human behavior.
It consists in incorporating a fundamental insight into all management intentions and practices: For employees, commitments to the company will only be possible if they appear as a clear means of achieving their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, this concept of employee motivation is only dealt with in the Motivational Functional Analysis study.
These studies have shown that they evaluate their businesses on the basis of a predetermined doxy, which allows them, through the image that says about the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life goals.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, managers can control, anticipate, and anticipate their "social performance" and put their HR management "on track."
In so doing, it creates fertile ground for the development of solid and efficient economic intelligence.
With his speech from Oslo: "just war," Obama earned praise from the right.
The American right on Friday welcomed a speech Barack Obama gave in Oslo the day before, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner had defended the concept of a "just war" against enemies of the United States.
Conservatives who initially mocked Obama's Oct. 9 award applauded the presidential speech this time, including Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
"I liked what he said," Palin, the muse of the right-wing Republican wing, told USA Today, adding that she herself had spoken out on the subject of "sometimes necessary" war in her memoirs, which are now being published.
War is, of course, the last thing Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
All terrorists should be apprehended there, he believes.
President Obama, who inherited two wars in Afghanistan and Iraq from his predecessor, George W. Bush, justified the deployment in Oslo on Thursday and used the speech to explain his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another of Obama's opponents, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really very good, congratulated the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who especially appreciated the President's reference to "the existence of evil in the world".
In a way, I thought the speech was quite historic," Gingrich said during an interview on "The Takeaway" radio show.
The former Congressman, whom some see as a possible Republican candidate in the 2012 presidential election, was thrilled to see the "left-wing president" remind members of the Nobel Prize Committee "that they themselves would not be free and could not present the peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
According to Michael Gerson, former speechwriter George W. Bush, now editor of the Washington Post, Obama delivered a "very American speech."
Not only did he present himself as a "citizen of the world" as always, but he "spoke like an American president" and reminded Europeans "that they live in a safe bubble that they did not create themselves, and that they are not doing much to preserve it," Gerson said.
Among the few right-wing malcontents is the Bush-era hawk, former UN ambassador John Bolton, who called the speech "monotonous, pompous, and uninspired," as he put it on the National Review Online website.
To the left of the president, for example, Democratic representative Dennis Kucinich is horrified at the sight of Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
"When we wrap war in the packaging of justice, we can easily justify the massacre of innocent people," he warned.
Nevertheless, the center-left press has a positive view of the president.
Although the Los Angeles Times continues to consider the awarding of the peace prize to Obama premature, it judged his performance to be an "overachievement," even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo Accords should serve as a guide to international decisions in conflict resolution, poverty and oppression," the California daily wrote.
Obama "delivered a speech that was necessary," the New York Times said, calling the speech "simple and enlightening."
Road hauliers: three marathons to deal to save supply delivery for Christmas.
After three marathon negotiations, the road haulage union and TLF, the only employers' organization that remained until the end, reached an agreement on Friday night that ended the call for a strike and the threat that hung over the supply of supplies for Christmas.
State Secretary for Transport Dominique Bussereau expressed "joy" at the signing of the agreement on Friday after several negotiations that began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, negotiators parted ways early on Friday morning, hoping that the text of the agreement would be signed as quickly as possible by the end of the morning.
This is despite the fact that three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) withdrew from the negotiations.
But it took more than six hours of the meeting, which began at 11 a.m., for everyone to agree and sign the text of the agreement at 6 p.m.
The conflict "would hurt businesses greatly" and "risk disrupting the end-of-year holidays," Bussereau said.
The text includes a wage increase of 4% for the lowest salaries (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest salaries (international transport).
The hourly wage for the lowest salaries increases from €8.72 to €9.06.
It's not much, but there's a lot of effort behind it, Patrice Clos (FO) explained.
Tonight we will instruct our members not to blockade, no blockades of supply centers.
But there may still be a few naysayers who are not satisfied," he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, welcomed the "right deal", although it was difficult to admit the increase in high salaries in view of international competition".
According to him, there will be an increase of 170 euros per month for the lowest wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest ones.
It is an agreement of common sense and respect for employees, declared CMaxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed the "historic agreement".
According to Richard Jaubert (CGT), this is an "acceptable compromise".
The agreement also foresees a 3% revalorisation of travel expenses and a report on the state of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will also allow a focus on the issue of the 13th salary and the modernisation of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled the "€100 million reduction in corporate payroll taxes" that was the subject of a government amendment to the 2009 budget bill, which was voted on overnight by the National Assembly Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate for an "identical" vote.
The signature allows this agreement to apply first to enterprises that are members of this organization, later to the entire sector, in the event of expansion by the Ministry of Labor.
It will take place "as soon as possible," Bussereau assured.
Only opposition from employers' organisations can hinder the process.
FNTR speaks of a "bad deal" as €100 million "has already been offered to the sector to offset part of the carbon tax."
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to act in an emergency not as a result of mutual analysis, but in order not to anger the turkey eaters in time for the approaching Christmas holidays, Unostra complained.
For Otre, the agreement threatens to "bury a large number of small and medium-sized enterprises in the industry" over the next 12 months.
RER A commuter trains: weekend traffic interruption, unions dissatisfied with the RATP proposals.
The disruption of service on the RER A commuter train line, the largest public transport line in France, will continue over the weekend, as Friday's negotiations between the unions and the RATP management on the second day of the strike did not produce any concrete results on the bonus claim.
On Saturday and Sunday, the days of the important shopping weekend before Christmas, trains will run only between 10 a.m. and 8 p.m., with every second train running on the main section (between La Défence and Nation), and only one train out of four outside this section.
The connection with SNCF will be cut off at Nanterre Préfecture and passengers will be forced to change trains.
Galeries Lafayette department stores, which expect over 200,000 customers every day, welcomed the fact that "the RATP has tried to secure connections with the big department stores".
The RER A line runs from west to east of the Paris metropolitan area.
The section managed by the RATP runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
On Friday, one train out of two was in operation during rush hour, and virtually no train ran during off-peak hours, as planned.
As on Thursday, the residents of Ile de France arranged differently and there was no confusion on the platforms.
So, early in the morning, there were far fewer people than usual at Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) station, not least because pupils and students were missing.
Jack Nbakina, an engineer, 29 from Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne), explained that he got up "an hour and a half early to make sure he arrived on time".
Saint-Lazare station was not overcrowded, the national railway SNCF announced, as a larger number of ushers and vigilantes were predicted.
RER A commuter trains operated by SNCF in the direction of or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or departed from Saint-Lazare station with a connection to the metro.
The next general assemblies of strikers will be held on Saturday and Sunday, at which the results of Friday afternoon meetings with the leadership, which the unions rated as "weak", will be assessed.
The RER management proposes negotiations on a special protocol for RER A commuter trains in all respects, the adjustment of working hours, the course of careers, etc.
But that's not the point for drivers who demand a well-deserved bonus, according to Thierry Garon (Trade Unions South).
The RATP even postponed proposals on the premium for the time being, which scandalized the CGT, saying that the management "was not able to solve the problem, whereas it was possible for tour operators and SNCF".
At a new meeting scheduled for Monday, "the conditions of professional conduct will be examined more closely", the RATP said.
Which is why union officials think the company is "making fun of weekend travellers".
In the morning, about 150 drivers occupied the works committee at its Paris headquarters.
The leadership, which until now had refused any discussion during the strike, therefore decided to meet in the interest of "calming".
The conflict threatens to spread to RER B on Tuesday after Unsa and the Independents announce a strike alert.
The unions are demanding a premium of between €120 (Unsa) and €150, including €30 variables (CGT, FO, CFDT, Sud (South), Indépendants (Independents)) and complaining about the deteriorating working conditions on this route, which carries a million passengers a day.
RER drivers earn between €2200 and €2700 of gross wages and €600 to €650 of bonuses for irregular working hours and for work on Sundays and public holidays.
The Turkish judiciary has dissolved for the Kurdish side, and this decision has serious consequences.
Turkey's Constitutional Court ruled on Friday to dissolve the country's main pro-Kurdish party. The decision immediately sparked protest demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could significantly complicate the government's task of reaching out to the Kurdish community in a friendly way to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Supreme Court President Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of hearings.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, needing a majority-seven votes to dissolve the party, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysela Tugluk, were banned from political life for five years.
At the same time, the judge announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Ms Tugluk and the confiscation of party property by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP has 21 seats (out of 500) in Parliament.
The party leadership had warned before the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than serve as MPs without political affiliation.
The ruling follows a trial initiated in 2007 by Court of Cassation Prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "orders" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is a legal political showcase for PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has no "basic connection" with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court's verdict comes as the government extends a hand of friendship to the Kurdish community, offering a series of measures to strengthen their rights and attempting to limit Kurdish support for the PKK to end the conflict.
The DTP leadership confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to renewed tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where many demonstrations have degenerated in recent weeks against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is being held into clashes with police.
Since the announcement of the justice ruling, thousands of demonstrators have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a major city in the southeast inhabited mostly by Kurds.
Police used tear gas grenades and water cannons, while demonstrators threw Molotov cocktails or fired stones from slingshots.
About a hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said the justice decision would only "deepen despair".
Turkey cannot solve this issue by banning the party, he said in the press.
The government, made up of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We are opposed to the dissolution of parties as a matter of principle.
It solves nothing, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
The decision is a complete blast of the democratic proposals launched by the government, commented political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we can expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for one of the deadliest attacks in northern Turkey, which killed seven soldiers three days earlier.
Snow can come
A pretty crunching winter, that's what Wolfgang Brauburger wants.
Not because he wants to bully citizens, says the head of the winter department of FES technical services.
But so that its employees can try and learn to control all vehicle technology.
This weekend could be the first time this could happen, according to meteorologists.
Over 300 employees and 120 vehicles are ready to take care of the snow and ice.
In doing so, FES is proceeding according to a precise plan.
As soon as it snows across the board in Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero, 20 so-called sections A of the bulk spreader will be dispatched, Brauburger explains.
These sections include main and transit routes such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
But also access points for firefighters, suburban public transport lines, pedestrian zones and downhill sections such as Atzelbergstraße.
The FES service starts at three o'clock in the morning.
If necessary, it is necessary to sprinkle with wet salt within a maximum of three hours, which holds better, something around 1040 kilometers.
That's why FES starts at three o'clock at night "so that the roads are clear when the traffic to work starts."
It's not easy when it doesn't start snowing until 7.30am.
Then we have a problem, says the head of the winter technical services department, "because no one is willing to make room for the spreaders".
Only when it doesn't snow so much are the access and interconnection roads, including Rat-Beil-Straße, in turn.
The last priority is given to side and minor roads.
Brauburger knows they'll complain there.
At five o'clock in the morning, FES infantrymen set out, preferably cleaning dangerous places and crossings.
FES usually cannot take care of all bike paths.
There is a special service in Frankfurt that monitors mainly bridges from 10 p.m. to 4.30 a.m., Brauburger says.
Since glaciers form on them quickly, the spreaders leave as soon as the temperature drops below two degrees.
If necessary, the police will also call them.
Cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The animal, two meters long and 1.50 meters high, ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelimbs with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing out of the ordinary.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues write in Thursday's issue of Science that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these physical features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial arid region of the supercontinent Pangaea.
Tawa opens a new window to earlier dinosaur evolution, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the kinship, distribution, and characteristics of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, unprecedented for Triassic deposits, said team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The find confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are very rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts don't share this enthusiasm without reservation.
The find is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
Many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the assignment of prehistoric dinosaurs is usually disputed.
Experts debate, for example, when lizards split into three most important lineages: carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor and birds, "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and herbivores Ornithischia (bird pans), which included Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
Tawa hallae is the original therpod after analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It exhibits an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, Nesbitt says.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, researchers found evidence of air sacs that the descendants of theropod birds have.
Thanks to air sacs, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since a related line of giant sauropod later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation was probably created by a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Since the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists deduced that lizards appeared there for the first time.
According to this, the three lines of development split early and spread from South America to all the continents, which at that time as the supercontinent Pangaea formed a single land mass.
The team found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods, along with Tawa hallae.
The three cannot be descended from one common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
One even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His conjecture could give a distorted picture, as many primitive dinosaur fossils remain in South America, and they are rarely found on other continents.
How dinosaurs proved that they evolved from a relatively rare reptile lineage to the ruling vertebrates on earth in the Earth's Middle Ages remains a mystery.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying lizards, and countless other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species evolved, while relatives died out and the Triassic-Jurassic interface.
The success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs adapted better so they could squeeze out the competition.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped another group of animals that had also evolved in the Triassic and had lived in the shadows ever since: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and the signatories are international.
The list includes professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna and Berkeley, California.
Associate professors from Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin and Bremen joined.
The police eviction of the occupied casino of Frankfurt's Goethe University caused a worldwide stir.
278 professors and lecturers at Goethe University, as well as universities across Germany, Europe and North and South America, are in solidarity with the protesting students on the Westend campus.
In a statement written in German and English, they "do not approve" of the police intervention instigated by the Presidium.
Because the walls and artwork were scrawled, university president Werner Müller-Estler had the building, which was occupied by striking students and lecturers last week, vacated.
Five students were injured.
The damage to the cause, the signatories believe, does not justify the "forcible dissolution of self-organized teaching of students and teachers by police commandos."
The eviction constitutes an "unacceptable interference" with the freedoms of research and science.
The exclusive focus on vandalism serves to "illegitimize and criminalize the protest" and distracts attention from the content.
The Presidium avoided the necessary discussion.
The speakers call for the criminal prosecution to be stopped.
It is claimed that the majority of strikers did not support material damage.
Justified protest
The youth of the Verdi trade union and the German Trade Union are also in solidarity with the students.
The protest is a legitimate expression of growing concern for one's future, says Alexander Klein, secretary of the Verdi Land Youth.
Hessian Science Minister Eva Kühne-Hörmann (CDU) has so far defended the actions of the university president and the police.
We are grateful to the University President.
Destruction and occupation are absolutely unacceptable means, she said on Thursday in Aktuellen Stunde (Current Hour) in the Wiesbaden Landtag.
We have sympathy for the protest, but we have no sympathy for vandalism," said CDU member Peter Beuth.
The opposition factions of the SPD, the Greens and the Linke saw it differently.
The CDU is taking painted walls as an excuse to criminalize protest, Janine Wissler (Linke) said.
Instead of dealing with the arguments and demands of the students, the eviction took place.
Linke has filed a motion calling on the Home Secretary to report on police deployment.
New Silicon-Valley
For many years it was a secret city, inaccessible to visitors from the West.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of the capital Moscow, in the Soviet Union, was a heavily guarded location where secret weapons research was conducted.
Today, this district with 216,000 inhabitants, 37 kilometers from the center of Moscow, is considered the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Important micro- and nanoelectronic research and production centers are located here.
Since September 2008, the representatives of Zelenograd have established contacts with the Frankfurt Science Center Riedberg - with university institutions and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Center (FIZ).
There were several reciprocal visits, and on Wednesday Zelenograd and Ridberg signed a "Protocol on Close Cooperation" in Frankfurt.
The Russian delegation was led by Moscow Deputy Mayor Yuri Roslyak and Zelenograd Prefect Anatoly Smirnov, while Edwin Schwarz, Chief Planning Officer, signed for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of FIZ and small and medium-sized enterprises engaged in scientific research will go to a seminar in Zelenograd.
Scientific exchange
This is an ongoing scientific exchange.
But it is also about economic relations.
FIZ companies will be allowed to establish themselves in the growing Russian market.
On the contrary, Russian scientific companies want to get contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of major Russian research institutes and companies.
These include the Moscow Institute of Electronic Technology, the large concerns Sitronics and Rossiyskaya Elektronika.
The district was founded in 1958 as a so-called "socialist planned city" for arms research.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") got its name from the forested hilly landscape in which research facilities are set.
Stuttgart brake
The dimension of Stuttgart 21 cannot be adequately prepared at all.
For supporters of the project, it is quite simply the "new heart of Europe".
Well. The S21 is more than the opening of a railway station, more than a monstrous structure that plunges the capital of Baden-Württemberg into desperate construction chaos for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was created from the spirit of the 80s.
Head stations with tracks that ended in the city centre were considered to be 19th century transport and technical fossils that act as brakes on modern rail transport, as it took enormous time to change locomotives from rear to front.
Stop, stop for a while, keep going - that's how it should work.
And that's why the main stations are disappearing: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: the transit station, which lies about halfway along the trans-European railway line between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava - hence the slogan about "the heart of Europe".
It really starts with the S21, although the visions of the 80s are no longer compatible with reality.
The very ambitious designers themselves recognized that in the Hessian and Bavarian cities the start of construction was almost unfinanceable.
Since there are modern shuttle trains with motor and control vehicles at both ends, the main stations no longer have problems with entering and exiting.
Still: It starts with Stuttgart 21 including the new ICE line to Ulm.
It was pushed through by state and local politicians.
The railways cooperate, also because the risks of the largest individual infrastructure project in the country are borne by the taxpayer and not by the state concern.
Urbanistically, the project can still be excused in some way.
A new urban space will be created, which - if we believe the computer pictures of the designers - will contain a lot of greenery.
For the rail transport system, the S21 is harmful.
The passable station and the construction of the line are intended for passenger transport, which - typically in the 80s - was attributed to a huge increase.
At that time, there was no competition from cheap flights.
However, modern transport policy must first and foremost be about strengthening freight transport, because rail transport is far more environmentally friendly than on-road transport.
But the new track is not suitable for freight trains due to steep climbs.
Even more serious is that the S21 indirectly affects many other railway projects.
A good six billion euros were to be buried in Swabia.
This is the official figure.
Experts consider ten to 15 billion to be realistic.
It is clear that in the next decade there will be a shortage of funding for additional nodal points and bottlenecks in the network.
There are sixty larger projects on the list of the Ministry of Transport.
One of the most important is the construction of a roughly 180-kilometre-long route through the Rhine Valley.
Since 1987, construction on this route has been carried out at a slow pace.
Here it would be necessary to push hard.
But the S21 will be like a brake.
The Rhine Valley line becomes the bottleneck of international freight traffic: right in the heart of Europe.
Government examines airport ruling
The state government has left it open in the Wiesbaden Landtag whether it will oppose the ruling of the Hessian Administrative Court (VGH) regarding the ban on night flights and have it revised.
The CDU/FDP coalition has commissioned experts to legally assess the more than 400-page VGH ruling, Economy Minister Dieter Posch (FDP) said.
VGH in Kassel today explained in writing that the state would have to modify the night-time flight ban in the event of the construction of the planned northwestern runway of Frankfurt Airport.
The authorisation of 17 flights between 11 p.m. and 5 a.m., as envisaged by the provincial government, does not correspond to the legally mandated protection of the population from night aircraft noise.
The coalition must decide by January 4 whether to request a review of the ruling.
The opposition criticized the postponement and urged government representatives to abandon the revision of the Federal Administrative Court in Leipzig.
SPD faction leader Torsten Schäfer-Gümbel called on the CDU and FDP to revisit the promises it made before the election to ban night flights. Otherwise, it can be classified as a "violation of the word".
It's damn hard if you can keep your word, Green Party leader Tarek Al-Wazir said, referring to the FDP's election slogan "We keep our word."
Minister Posch rejected Schäfer-Gümbel's reproach, saying that the provincial government is trying to get to its night flights by "twisting the law and tricks".
Precise legal control takes time.
The coalition does not want to work on the basis of a "quick first impression".
We need a realistic decision, said Stefan Müller (FDP).
His faction's statements on the ban on night flights have never been what the opposition is reporting.
U.S. Banks Repay Aid
America's crisis-stricken big banks are freeing themselves from state shackles.
Bank of America repaid a total of $45 billion (about 30 billion euros) in aid from the Tarp bank rescue fund on Wednesday.
According to a CNBC report, Citigroup is also planning to repay state aid.
Thus, the institutes want to get rid of the restrictions that have occurred by accepting money - limiting the payment of bonuses to managers and the payment of high fees.
