Worlds of dreams
Some see images and hear voices in the waking state that others do not see and hear.
It is not only mentally ill or drugged people who blur the boundaries between imagination and reality.
As long as this happens in sleep, everything is fine.
If we lie with our eyes closed in our dark room, we are allowed to surround ourselves with the wildest fantasies and fantasy delusions.
However, those who experience dream states in wakefulness, see and hear things that others do not see and do not hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicted, or at least a weirdo.
However, such images and voices do not arise only in the mentally ill or in drug intoxication.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels occasionally blur the boundaries between dream, imagination, and reality.
Dream-altered states of consciousness can occur in various forms, at best we call them visions, at worst delusions.
Although the initiator and effect may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New-Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic states of delirium, psychoses and hallucinations can be derived from similar processes.
Hallucinations or visions occur when the balance of neuronal transmitters in the brain – primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – is derailed and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often in schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity doesn't have much over him
The connection between error and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since antiquity.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in the waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychology, noted in 1861 "the great similarity of delirium with dream states", for Sigmund Freud dream was even "psychosis, with all nonsense, delusions, deception of the senses".
It's autumn 2001, Henning T. is turning into a comic book character.
His body is two-dimensional and garishly colored.
Gravity has no power over him, hovering near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devil figures with blood-red grimaces, baring their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, fiery boots, throw him against walls, feel pain all over his body.
Loud, evil voices come from the walls and from the radio.
He can no longer stand voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. rips two cables out of the stereo, knots them into a loop and fastens it to a hook on the ceiling.
He stands on one of the speakers and puts the loop around his neck.
Jumps.
The loop loosens.
Learn, voices shout in chorus, tearing his eardrums, "go to the clinic and get treated!"
Today, Henning T. is 40 years old, has experienced six acute psychoses, the last 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
LSD was launched.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective paranoic psychosis, besides he is manic-depressive, takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness and has been married for three years.
"In psychosis, I experienced the worst fear and the deepest doubts," he says.
Ghosts are a terrible reality
About one percent of people fall ill with schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is the second most frequently treated disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outer world, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, size illusions, relationship illusions or the illusion of persecution.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices - voices that command, comment or conduct dialogues.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The affected person is not able to distinguish the important from the unimportant, the brain can not filter out disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the General Psychiatry Clinic of the University Clinic of Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, becomes, as in a dream, overwhelmed by events and cannot actively form them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is usually not possible with them, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is impossible.
Experiencing a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, says Fuchss, "however, the sensory and spatial structure of reality, which one perceives in psychosis, remains essentially preserved."
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of experience occurs in a real framework.
Scientists are still faced with the puzzle of why exactly our brain does such flips.
Emergencies can lead to a person's short-term loss of touch with reality, Fuchs says.
But not everyone develops into psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists assume that affected people have minimal brain damage.
It is thought that neuronal maturation of the brain will be damaged at an early stage of development, for example by viral diseases of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
However, it remains a mystery how a malfunction of the neuronal system, which has not manifested itself for many years, occurs.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis, if there is a predisposition to it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis, as they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brain boils
The crazy thing is that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations, and to get rid of them, they swallow expensive medications, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lübeck.
Whether we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he interpreted his results in the book "Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf" (The Unreal World in Our Heads).
Hallucinations are typical accompanying phenomena of psychoses, but also surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to psychological disorders such as borderline personality or depression, diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's or brain trauma are also common.
Surprisingly, the brain of a healthy person itself hallucinates under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Casten, consist of the contents of thoughts that are normally repressed.
They arise when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are too active or not suppressed enough; If our brain boils or when stimulation is missing.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like brain damage or psychosis.
But also withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries about love or other exceptional states.
In more recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported that they had experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the local grammar school.
Actually a completely normal girl.
If it weren't for the patterns and voices.
During breaks, she may be approached by a wheelbarrow with long, dark hair.
When she answers him, her classmates look at her with surprise - no one but her can see and hear this boy.
This shy girl thinks she's a stiff dreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows that.
He is awake, he hears and sees the boy, just as he hears and sees the girl sitting next to him in the pew.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, he sometimes asks.
But he knows that this boy and other delusions are not real and will disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are rather daunting
Often delusions are a burden.
When she sits in class, she cannot watch the lessons many times, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is introducing a new classmate, while he explains to everyone else audibly and visibly on the blackboard mathematical equations.
At night, the apparitions are rather daunting.
When she waits in her dark room for a sleep that rarely comes too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already asleep, whether the images she sees, the grimaces, or the girl with bleeding cuts on her hands and feet, appear before her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, they shout at the characters.
She doesn't tell her parents and friends about it, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She graduated from high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she contacted the psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she has not gone mad.
Delusions are also an art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or stimuli are taken away, they are more likely to hallucinate, Kasten says.
I believe that the brain then does not have enough work and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she called Dad since she was thinking wasn't her own father.
Because visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same brain regions that process real sensations and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is also displayed there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why it feels so real."
Night dreams are also evaluated by Kasten as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten advises his patients to rate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
Borderline state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our world too conscious, imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician of the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic at the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a severe, agonizing disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - a mirage is also an art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard investigated the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of altered consciousness to dreams.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictional dreams that the person considers real and cannot even distinguish retrospectively from the waking state.
Oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or illness, for example, polyradicular inflammation patients who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
When a person is threatened with the loss of the world and himself, even by a persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between a dream and a hallucination.
Because it is not possible to manage a situation in reality, the worlds change, but the real situation becomes present in the imagination.
An intense form of sensory support and sensory transfer in some unbearable situation that allows us humans to transform ourselves into loss of consciousness in an instant.
Everything is real, even later in memories
The art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (The Exchange of the Heart) as a rescue action of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, his consciousness embarked on a journey of several days, with his body lying motionless in intensive care.
Claussen immerses himself in the world he has created, visiting strange times and places: He becomes an old man bedridden, in a train sanatorium, a robot guarding his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility, which produces narcotics from blood.
A Greek kidnaps him on a motorcycle to his homeland, surfs a firn in the Alps in a hospital bed and meets a Korean mafioso.
He immerses himself completely in an imaginary plot, everything is real, even later in memories.
For Claussen, these inner paths are fundamentally different from any dream.
A dream is a different state, it describes its experience.
In contrast to dreams, the memories of those mental journeys are still clearly clear years later and in insignificant details.
