75% of working mothers have work problems related to motherhood.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women wishing to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and working career of Spanish women', carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75, and the results are unequivocal: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities on the labour market due to motherhood.
The study highlights that at the beginning of cohabitation, there are many differences of opinion on the number of children, depending on whether they work or not, and also according to the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job start living with a partner earlier, give birth to their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable jobs, especially in the public sector, postpone cohabitation and motherhood and have fewer children.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years after the beginning of cohabitation with their partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving stable employment and have therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less influence on the time it takes to start living with a partner," explains Margarita Delgado, who researches at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage andthe birth of a child is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 and 32.1, respectively.
"There is yet another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education marry and give birth to their first child before finding stable employment, while women with secondary or higher education do the opposite: they prefer to get a stable job rather than get married and have their first child," says Delgado.
