The handbrake assistance system is already a mandatory equipment.
As in the case of the anti-lock braking system ABS, it will be with ESP stability control, auxiliary handbrake systems, all this will become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, it is already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the others the deadline for closing the shortage is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase pedestrian protection and works in such a way that it can help avoid many collisions.
The handbrake assist system increases the brake pressure in an emergency, which the system detects when the driver presses.
But he is not always able to keep this pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by auto parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident did not apply the brakes before the collision, and half of them did not fully use the force of the brake.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of device, up to 1 100 pedestrian-related fatalities per year could be avoided.
The reduction in this number will be even more striking – according to calculations, one in four accidents affecting people would be avoided – following the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicle will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, in addition to light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be avoided, the device will act as intensely as possible on the brake, reducing the risk of damage to a minimum.
